The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, March 05, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, March 4: Berger Paints Ltd, Punjab National Bank, Vijaya Bank and US-based Principal Financial group will form a joint-venture company to foray into insurance broking. The parties would sign a shareholders agreement and share-subscription pact tomorrow, Vijaya Bank informed the National Stock Exchange today. Meanwhile, the board of Berger Paints has approved the companys foray into insurance brokerage and pension-funds business with investments of up to Rs 30 crore.																								 New Delhi, March 4: The government today cleared 24 foreign direct investment proposals worth Rs 190.93 crore, including the Rs 140 crore investment by Korean confectionery firm, Lotte, to acquire resident shares via a public issue.																								 New Delhi, March 4: The Monopolies and Restrictive Trade Practices Commission has issued a notice to Unit Trust on a complaint challenging UTIs decision to terminate its Childrens Gift Growth Fund, 1986, with effect from April 1, 2004.																								 New Delhi, March 4: The Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority today allowed PSUs and private firms with a capital of Rs 10 lakh to Rs 3 crore to bargain for a special discount of 5 per cent in exchange of agency commission or brokers remuneration, when they cover their risks directly with a general insurer.																								 New Delhi, March 4: Retaining the same number while changing the service provider may become a reality for subscribers with the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India deciding to issue a consultation paper on number portability within a month.																								 New Delhi, March 4: The Tata group is looking at a broadband company, which has 30,000 broadband customers and 1,50,000 ISP customers, for a possible acquisition and the deal may be concluded in a month or two, said a company official.																								 Mumbai, March 4: Coates of India Ltds board has recommended a 35 per cent dividend for the year ended December 2003, which is subject to shareholders approval.
